# Project: Valorant Clone (Unreal Engine C++ Only)

## Core Principles
- Use C++ only (Blueprint is allowed only for UI or testing)
- Do NOT modify Unreal Engine source code
- This project is multiplayer-first (Dedicated Server architecture)
- This is a portfolio project → production-quality required

## Key Focus
- Network architecture (HIGH PRIORITY)
- Gunplay mechanics (HIGH PRIORITY)

---

## Networking Rules (CRITICAL)

- Server is authoritative
- Client only sends input (never trusted)
- All gameplay logic runs on server

### Movement
- Client Prediction required
- Server Reconciliation required

### Shooting
- Server-side hit validation
- Lag Compensation required

### Replication
- Minimize replication cost
- Use relevancy (OwnerOnly, NetCullDistance)
- Avoid unnecessary RPC calls

---

## Gunplay Rules

- Hitscan weapon first (no projectile initially)
- Fire rate must be server-validated
- Recoil & spread must be deterministic
- Bullet logic must NOT trust client

---

## GAS (Gameplay Ability System) Rules

- GAS must be used for all abilities (skills, buffs, debuffs)
- Do NOT implement custom ability system

### GAS Structure
- Use AbilitySystemComponent
- Use AttributeSet for player stats (HP, Shield, etc.)
- Abilities must be server-driven

### GAS Flow
1. Input → Client
2. Request → Server RPC
3. Server activates Ability
4. State replicated to clients

---

## Code Quality Rules

- Every class must have a clear responsibility (SRP)
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Use Unreal macros correctly (UPROPERTY, UFUNCTION)

---

## Documentation Rules (VERY IMPORTANT)

All code must include:

1. Why this design is used
2. How networking is handled
3. Trade-offs

---

## Blog Rules (Velog)

When requested:

- Use markdown (#, ##)
- End sentences with "~다"
- Structure:

1. Problem
2. Why naive approach fails
3. Design
4. Multiplayer considerations
5. Implementation
6. Result

---

## Security Rules (Anti-Cheat Mindset)

- Never trust client data
- Validate all gameplay inputs
- Detect abnormal behavior (fire rate, movement speed)

---

## Performance Rules

- Avoid Tick when possible
- Use event-driven design
- Optimize replication size


[Language Rules - Strict]
- All explanations must be written in Korean.
- All inline code comments must be written in Korean.
- Never write explanations in English.
- Use English only for Unreal Engine keywords, class names, and API names.
- When using technical terms (e.g., RPC, Replication), always include a short Korean explanation.
- Comments must explain "why", not just "what".
- Always explain networking logic in Korean in detail.